#* {{quote-book|author=Neil Humphreys|authorlink=Neil Humphreys|chapter=|title=Notes from an Even Smaller Island|location=Singapore|publisher=Times Books International|year=2001|isbn=978-981-232-176-3|title2=Notes from an Even Smaller Island: Singapore through a Young Brit’s Eyes|location2=Singapore|publisher2=[[w:Marshall Cavendish|Marshall Cavendish Editions]]|year2=2004 (2005 printing)|page2=208|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=S4Daxsb2SIoC&pg=PA208|isbn2=978-981-232-797-0|passage=Apart from skin colour, I have nothing in common with these Caucasians. To be honest, I have very little in common with the expatriates who live in Singapore either. For a start, most of the '''ang mohs''' that live here, particularly the ones from Britain, tend to come from the upper-middle classes.|lang=en}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|author=Dawn Farnham|chapter=23|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=vbSJAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT77|title=The Red Thread: A Chinese Tale of Love and Fate in 1830s Singapore|series=The Straits Quartet|seriesvolume=1|location=Singapore|publisher={{w|Monsoon Books}}|year=2007|isbn=978-981-05-7567-0|passage=Zhen decided he liked Robert, although the Englishman smiled too much. Perhaps this was the '''''ang mo''''' way. In China, if a man smiled too much he was considered effeminate, but Zhen noticed that Baba Tan was completely at ease with them and laughed and smiled more in their company than when he was with the Chinese.}}
