#* {{quote-book|lang=en|author=Edmund M. Schirmer|chapter=Finding Home Again|title=When there were Tigers in Singapore: A Family Saga of the Japanese Occupation|location=Singapore|publisher=[[w:Marshall Cavendish|Marshall Cavendish Editions]]|year=2011|page=38|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=lfuIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|isbn=978-981-4398-17-6|passage=[H]e attracted the attention of a food vendor and pointed at a pot consisting of different cuts of meat stewed in a dark soy sauce broth, served with flat rice noodles on the side. The food vendors, or hawkers, smiled at each other beatifically while ladling out the hot soup and meat in a bowl. They were probably thinking something on the lines of, "The stupid '''''angmoh''''' doesn't know what he is about to eat!" '''''Angmoh''''', literally meaning "red hair," is the Hokkien Chinese collective term for Caucasians.}}
